{"title_page": "One (U2 song)", "text_new": "{{short description|1992 single by U2}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name = One\n| cover = U2 One.png\n| type = single\n| artist = [[U2]]\n| album = [[Achtung Baby]]\n| B-side= \"Lady with the Spinning Head (UV1)\"\n| released = {{Start date|1992|02|24|df=y}}\n| format = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[cassette single|cassette]]|[[7-inch vinyl]]|[[12-inch maxi single|12-inch vinyl maxi]]}}\n| recorded = October 1990 \u2013 September 1991\n| studio = \n*[[Hansa Ton Studios]] (Berlin)\n*Elsinore ([[Dalkey]])\n*[[Windmill Lane Studios]] (Dublin)\n| genre = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length = {{Duration|m=4|s=36}}\n| label = [[Island Records|Island]]\n| composer = U2\n| lyricist = [[Bono]]\n| producer = [[Daniel Lanois]] with [[Brian Eno]]\n| prev_title    = [[Mysterious Ways (song)|Mysterious Ways]]\n| prev_year     = 1991\n| next_title    = [[Even Better Than the Real Thing]]\n| next_year     = 1992\n| misc = {{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = U2 One.ogg\n}}{{External music video|{{YouTube|ftjEcrrf7r0|\"One\"}}\n | type = single\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''One'''\" is a song by Irish [[Rock music|rock]] band [[U2]]. It is the third track from their 1991 album ''[[Achtung Baby]]'', and it was released as the record's third single in February 1992. During the album's recording sessions at [[Hansa Studios]] in Berlin, conflict arose between the band members over the direction of U2's sound and the quality of their material. Tensions almost prompted the band to break up until they achieved a breakthrough with the improvisation of \"One\"; the song was written after the band members were inspired by a chord progression that guitarist [[the Edge]] was playing in the studio. The lyrics, written by lead singer [[Bono]], were inspired by the band members' fractured relationships and the [[German reunification]]. Although the lyrics ostensibly describe \"disunity\", they have been interpreted in other ways.\n\n\"One\" was released as a [[charity record|benefit single]], with proceeds going towards [[HIV/AIDS research|AIDS research]]. The song topped the [[Irish Singles Charts]], the Canadian ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles chart and the US ''Billboard'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Album Rock Tracks]] and [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] charts. It also peaked at number three in New Zealand, number four in Australia, number seven on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and number ten on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. In promotion of the song, the band filmed several music videos, although they were not pleased until a third was created.\n\nThe song was acclaimed by critics upon its release, and it has since been featured in polls of the greatest songs of all time. U2 has performed \"One\" at most of their tour concerts since the song's live debut in 1992, and it has appeared in many of the band's [[concert film]]s. In a live setting, \"One\" is often used by the group to promote human rights or [[social justice]] causes, and the song lends its namesake to Bono's charitable organisation, [[ONE Campaign|One Campaign]]. In 2005, U2 re-recorded the song as part of a duet with [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] recording artist [[Mary J. Blige]] on her album ''[[The Breakthrough]]''.\n\n==Writing and recording==\nIn October 1990, U2 arrived in Berlin on the eve of [[German reunification]] to begin the recording sessions for ''Achtung Baby'' at [[Hansa Studios]].{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}} Expecting to be inspired by a \"[[New Europe (political expression)|New Europe]]\" and the reuniting city, the band instead found the mood to be bleak and soon conflict arose over their musical direction and the quality of their material. While bassist [[Adam Clayton]] and drummer [[Larry Mullen, Jr.]] preferred a sound similar to U2's previous work, vocalist [[Bono]] and guitarist [[the Edge]] were inspired by European [[industrial music|industrial]] and [[electronic dance music]] of the time and were advocating a change.{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}} The band also had difficulty developing demos and musical ideas into completed songs.{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}} Bono and the Edge believed the lack of progress was the fault of the band, while Clayton and Mullen Jr. believed the problem was the quality of the songs.{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}} Mullen said he \"thought this might be the end\" of the band.{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote=\"At the instant we were recording it, I got a very strong sense of its power. We were all playing together in the big recording room, a huge, eerie ballroom full of ghosts of the war, and everything fell into place.  It was a reassuring moment, when everyone finally went, 'oh great, this album has started.' It's the reason you're in a band \u2013 when the spirit descends upon you and you create something truly affecting. 'One' is an incredibly moving piece. It hits straight into the heart.\"\n| source = \u2014[[The Edge]], on the recording of \"One\"{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}}\n| width  = 25em\n| align  = left\n| style = padding:10px;}}\n\nUltimately, a breakthrough in the sessions was achieved. While [[Jam sessions|jamming]] on a song called \"Sick Puppy\"\u2014an early version of \"[[Mysterious Ways (song)|Mysterious Ways]]\"\u2014the band tried different [[chord progression]]s for the [[bridge (music)|bridge]].{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}}<ref name=\"FTSD\">{{cite video | people= U2, [[Davis Guggenheim]] (Director) |title= [[From the Sky Down]] |medium = film | publisher = [[BBC Worldwide]] Canada |date=2011 |time= 57:49}}</ref> The jam stopped and the Edge tried playing them alone on an acoustic guitar, as \"everyone was trying to decide if they were any good.\"<ref name=\"FTSD\" /> At the suggestion of producer [[Daniel Lanois]], the Edge played two separate sections sequentially. The band liked the way it flowed and decided to try and play it together. Speaking of the improvisation, the Edge said, \"suddenly something very powerful [was] happening in the room.\"<ref name=\"FTSD\" /> He added, \"Everyone recognized it was a special piece. It was like we'd caught a glimpse of what the song could be.\"<ref name=\"blender500\" /> Soon afterwards, the band had developed the piece of music into \"One\".{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}}{{Sfn | Flanagan | 1996 | pp = 6\u201311}}  Bono recalls that \"the melody, the structure\u2014the whole thing was done in 15 minutes\".{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}}  He also stated that the lyrics \"just fell out of the sky, a gift\"; the concept was inspired by the band members' fracturing relationships,<ref name=\"legends\">{{cite episode|title=U2|series=[[VH1's Legends|Legends]]|network=[[VH1]] | season = 1| number = 6| airdate = 11 December 1998 | quote = Maybe it summed up the way we felt as a band, trying to kind of go somewhere, but not being able to at the time.}}</ref> the German reunification,<ref>{{cite news| title = Beyonce, U2 draw fans at MTV Europe Music Awards|url= https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2009-11-05-MTV-europe-music-awards_N.htm | newspaper= [[USA Today]]|author= [[Associated Press]]| date= 5 November 2009}}</ref> and Bono's scepticism of the [[hippie]] idea of \"oneness\". Bono later sent a note to the [[Dalai Lama]] declining an invitation to a festival called ''Oneness'', incorporating a line from the song: \"One\u2014but not the same\".{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}}  The song's writing inspired the band and changed their outlook on the recording sessions. Mullen Jr. said the song reaffirmed the band's \"blank page approach\" to recording and reassured the band that all was not lost.{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}}\n\n{{Quote box \n|quote=\"There was melancholy about it but there was also strength. One is not about oneness, it's about difference. It's not the old hippie idea of 'let's all live together.' It is a much more [[punk rock]] concept. It's anti-romantic: 'we are one but not the same. We get to carry each other.' It's a reminder that we have no choice. I'm still disappointed when people hear the chorus line as 'got to' rather than 'we get to carry each other.' Like it or not, the only way out of here is if I give you a leg up the wall and you pull me after you. There's something very unromantic about that.\n| width=25em|\n| align = right\n|source =\u2014[[Bono]], on the recording of \"One\"{{ Sfn | McCormick |2006 | pp =224}}}}\nFollowing the song's initial improvisation, tapes of the recording sessions were delivered to assisting producer [[Brian Eno]] to gather his input;{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}}  Eno spent extended periods of time away from the sessions before visiting to review songs, and he believed that distancing himself from the work allowed him to provide the band with a fresh perspective on their material each time he rejoined them.<ref name=\"eno\">{{cite journal| title= Eno|journal= Propaganda| issue= 16| date= June 1992}}</ref> The band were rather anxious about the quality of their material, but when Eno arrived in Berlin, they were surprised to hear that he liked most of the tapes.{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}}  However, as Bono recalls, Eno said, \"There's just one song I really despise, and that's 'One'.\"{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}}  Eno felt that they needed to deconstruct the song.{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}}\n\nThe band returned to [[Dublin]] in 1991 to record at the \"Elsinore\" mansion on the [[Dalkey]] coastline.{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 224\u20135, 232}}  The band continued to work on the song there, adding various [[overdub]]s, but not finding a [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]] they were satisfied with.{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}}  The Edge thought that they had the foundation for the song, but that it needed \"foreground\".{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}}  Eno interceded, explaining to the group that \"One\" was among the sessions' tracks in which \"The song has gone, whatever it is you liked about this song is not there anymore\", and that the track had \"disappeared under layers of overdubs\".<ref name=\"eno\" /> He created his own mix, which gave the band a better idea of an arrangement they liked.{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}}  Eno wanted the band to remove the melancholy elements of the song and persuaded them to remove the acoustic guitar from the song.{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}} He also worked with Lanois and the Edge to \"undermine the 'too beautiful' feeling\", which is why they added the \"crying guitar parts that have an aggression to them\".{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 216, 221}}\n\n[[Flood (producer)|Flood]], the sessions' [[Audio engineering|engineer]], was unconvinced by the song's mix, saying he \"was the nagging doubter. I always felt it was a bit straight, until we did the final mix.\"{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}}  The final mix was completed at [[Windmill Lane Studios]] in September 1991 on the last night of the album's recording sessions,{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}}{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 224\u20135, 232}} when some last minute additions were made. Bono did not like a line in the vocals and spent most of the day re-recording it.{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}} Later, after the song's mix had just been completed by the production team, the Edge came up with a guitar part he wanted to add to the song's end near the lyric \"Love is a temple\".{{Sfn | Stokes | 2005 | pp = 98\u2013100}}{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 224\u20135, 232}}  After convincing the production team to allow the addition, the Edge played the part once and had it mixed in ten minutes later.{{Sfn | McCormick | 2006 | pp = 224\u20135, 232}}\n\n==Composition==\n\"One\" is a rock [[ballad]] played in a 4/4 [[time signature]] at a [[tempo]] of 91 beats per minute.  The verse follows a [[chord progression]] of Am\u2013D5\u2013F[[Major seventh chord|maj<sub>7</sub>]]\u2013G while the chorus follows C\u2013Am\u2013Fmaj<sub>7</sub>\u2013C.<ref name=\"musicnotes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/scorchVPE.asp?ppn=SC0030381 |title=U2 \u2013 One Sheet Music |work=Musicnotes |accessdate=22 April 2010}} Note: Software required to view the page.</ref>\n\nBono described the song's theme as such: \"It is a song about coming together, but it's not the old hippie idea of 'Let's all live together.' It is, in fact, the opposite. It's saying, We are one, but we're not the same. It's not saying we even want to get along, but that we have to get along together in this world if it is to survive. It's a reminder that we have no choice\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-09-12/entertainment/ca-34478_1_achtung-baby|title=U2's Pride (In The Name of Songs)|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=Robert|last=Hilburn|authorlink=Robert Hilburn|date=12 September 1993|at=section Calendar, p. 62|accessdate=11 October 2011}}</ref> The Edge described it on one level as a \"bitter, twisted, vitriolic conversation between two people who've been through some nasty, heavy stuff\".<ref name=\"one\">McCormick (2006), pp. 221, 224.</ref> On another level, he suggested that the line \"we get to carry each other\" introduces \"grace\" to the song and that the wording \"get to\" (instead of \"got to\") is essential, as it suggests that it is a privilege to help one another, not an obligation.<ref name=\"one\" /> The band have been told by many fans that they played the song at their weddings, prompting Bono to respond, \"Are you mad? It's about splitting up!\"<ref name=\"one\" /> There was some speculation that the song described a conversation between a father and his HIV-positive gay son, based on the connection of the song to [[David Wojnarowicz]], a gay artist who died of [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]].<ref name=\"intoheart\">Stokes (2005), pp. 98\u2013100</ref> In 2005, Bono said \"It's a father-and-son story. I tried to write about someone I knew who was coming out and was afraid to tell his father. It's a religious father and son.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Bono on the Records|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Wenner|first=Jann|authorlink=Jann Wenner|date=3 November 2005|issue=986|pages=60}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\"One\" was released as the album's third single in February 1992 as a [[charity record|benefit single]], with all of the band's royalties being donated to different [[HIV/AIDS research|AIDS research]] organisations for each country in which the single was released.<ref name=\"record-aids\">{{cite news|title=One Small Step for Mankind|newspaper=[[The Record (Bergen County)|The Record]]|first=Barbara|last=Jaeger|date=13 March 1992}}</ref><ref name=\"globe-aids\">{{cite news|title=Yoko Ono's CD set serves up some surprises|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|first=Steve|last=Morse|date=28 February 1992}}</ref> The group's manager [[Paul McGuinness]] commented on their decision: \"The band feels that [AIDS] is the most pressing issue of the day, and we really have to focus people's attention to the AIDS plague that has been with us for 10 years.\"<ref name=\"record-aids\" /> To promote [[safe sex]], U2 sold [[condom]]s bearing the album title ''Achtung Baby'' at their [[Zoo TV Tour]] concerts.<ref name=\"globe-aids\" /> The cover of the single release is a photograph by David Wojnarowicz. The photograph depicts [[American bison|buffaloes]] falling off a cliff after being chased by Native American hunters.<ref name=\"globe-aids\" /> The single's liner notes explain that Wojnarowicz \"identifies himself and ourselves with the buffalo, pushed into the unknown by forces we cannot control or even understand\".<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=One |publisher=[[Island Records]] |id= |location=United States |date=1992 |others=[[U2]] |type=Compact disc}}</ref>\n\nThe single reached number seven in the [[UK Singles Chart]], number ten in the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and number one on the US [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Album Rock Tracks]]<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p5723/charts-awards/billboard-singles|pure_url=yes}} |title=U2: Charts & Awards: Billboard Singles |work=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=14 December 2009}}</ref> and [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] charts.<ref name=\"usmodernrock\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=u2|chart=all}}|title=One&nbsp;\u2013 U2|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=22 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Music videos===\nThree music videos were created for \"One\". The first, directed by [[Anton Corbijn]], was filmed in Berlin and features the band members performing at Hansa Studios interspersed with footage of [[Trabant]]s (an East German automobile they became fond of as a symbol for a changing Europe) and shots of them dressed in [[Drag (clothing)|drag]]. Bono explained that the idea to crossdress \"had been based on the idea that if ''U2 can't do this'', we've got to do it!\", and it was fostered by the group's experiences dressing in drag for the [[Carnival of Santa Cruz de Tenerife]].<ref>Flanagan (1996), p. 58</ref> However, the band pulled the video, fearing the single's status as an AIDS benefit would result in critics finding AIDS-related interpretations of the video. The Edge explained, \"We didn't want to be involved in putting back the AIDS issue into the realm of sexuality... It wasn't worth the risk of people imagining we were saying something about the AIDS issue through the drag footage, which was totally not what we were trying to say.\"<ref>Cogan (2008), p. 27</ref>\n\nThe second video was directed by [[Mark Pellington]]. It comprises images of blooming flowers, the title word in several languages, and slow-motion footage of [[American bison|buffaloes]] running, leading up to Wojnarowicz's \"Falling Buffalo\" photograph. Much like for the first video, the band did not believe Pellington's video would be good for promoting the single.<ref name=\"flan55\">Flanagan (1996), p. 55</ref>\n\nThe group filmed a third video in an attempt to appeal to a broader audience. It was directed by ''[[Rattle and Hum]]'' director [[Phil Joanou]] and was primarily filmed in early March 1992 at Nell's, a [[Manhattan]] nightclub.<ref name=\"flan55\" /><ref name=\"mcg145\">McGee (2008), p. 145</ref> The video depicts Bono sitting at a table smoking a [[cheroot]] and drinking beer, interspersed with footage of the band performing in concert.<ref name=\"mcg145\" /> While Bono was filmed, the rest of the band, along with models and [[transvestite]]s, attended a party in the basement, awaiting their turns to be filmed. However, they were never called to the set and by 3 a.m., they realised that the video was to focus on Bono.<ref>Flanagan (1996), pp. 56\u201357</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Windmill Lane 1994crop2.jpg|thumb|right|200px|In 1994, a fan wrote the song's lyrics on the sidewalk leading up to [[Windmill Lane Studios]] in blue chalk.]]\nAfter the release of ''Achtung Baby'', critics praised \"One\". In its review of the album, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called the song \"biting and unprecedentedly emotional\" and opined that its \"extravagant stylings and wild emotings [...] put it among Bono's most dramatic moments on record\".<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,316330,00.html|title=Achtung Baby|journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Bill|last=Wyman|date=29 November 1991|accessdate=2 May 2009|issue=94}}</ref> In its review of the album, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called the song a \"radiant ballad\", noting that \"Few bands can marshal such sublime power, but it's just one of the many moments on ''Achtung Baby'' when we're reminded why, before these guys were the butt of cynical jokes, they were rock & roll heroes\u2014as they still are.\"<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/achtung-baby-19920109|title=U2's 'Achtung Baby': Bring the Noise|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=Elysa|last=Gardner|date=9 January 1992|issue=621|accessdate=26 April 2010|page=51}}</ref> [[Niall Stokes]] of ''[[Hot Press]]'' gave an enthusiastic review of the song, calling it one of the album's tracks \"whose potency defies equivocations\". Stokes said the song, both upon initial and repeated listens, \"seems transcendent, a magnificent synthesis of elements, words and music, rhythm, instrumentation arrangement and intonation combine to create something that speaks a language beyond logic, the definitive language of emotional truth\". He said the melody was reminiscent of [[Led Zeppelin]] and the vocals evoked memories of [[Al Green]] and [[the Rolling Stones]] circa \"[[Sympathy for the Devil]]\". Stokes could not single out what made the song so \"utterly inspirational\", but said it was \"soul music that avoids the obvious cliches of the genre and cuts to the core\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review: Achtung Baby|journal=[[Hot Press]]|first=Niall|last=Stokes|authorlink=Niall Stokes|date=13 November 1991}}</ref>\n\n''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' called Bono's singing on the song a \"quieter moment\" that has \"never been so persuasively tender\".<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rocksbackpages.com/article.html?ArticleID=10465|title=U2: Achtung Baby|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|first=Mat|last=Snow|date=December 1991|issue=63|accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref> The ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' wrote that the song \"builds with the stately grandeur of a [[Roy Orbison]] ballad\" and that Bono's lyric \"We're one / But we're not the same\" is one of \"pithiest insights yet about the contradiction of marriage\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/chi-u2november91,0,2879134.story |title=U2 Loosens Up |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |first=Greg |last=Kot |authorlink=Greg Kot |date=17 November 1991}}</ref> The ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' called the track \"sorrowful\" and compared it to music by the Rolling Stones.<ref name=\"orlsent\">{{cite news |title=Achtung Baby |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |first=Patty |last=Gettelman |date=6 November 1991}}</ref> [[Robert Hilburn]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called the \"disillusioned\" track one of the album's high points.<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/61547027.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Nov+17%2C+1991&author=ROBERT+HILBURN&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&edition=&startpage=58&desc=U2%27s+Daring+Descent+Into+Darkness|title=U2's Daring Descent into Darkness|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=Robert |last=Hilburn|authorlink=Robert Hilburn|date=17 November 1991|accessdate=31 December 2009}} Note: A subscription is required to access the article.</ref> [[Denise Sullivan]] of [[Allmusic]] wrote that the song was \"among U2's finest recordings\", and she praised its \"lyrical simplicity, heart-rending vocal delivery, and evocative instrumentation\". She called the Edge's guitar playing \"unusually warm and soulful\".<ref>{{cite web | url = {{Allmusic|class=song|id=t1541604|pure_url=yes}} | title = Song Review: \"One\" | website = [[Allmusic]] | first = Denise | last = Sullivan | accessdate = 3 May 2010}}</ref> In the 1992 [[Pazz & Jop]] critics' poll in ''[[The Village Voice]]'', \"One\" placed at number eight on the \"Best Single\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/pjres92.php|title=The 1992 Pazz & Jop Critics Poll|work=[[Robert Christgau|robertchristgau.com]]|accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, [[Axl Rose]] told ''[[RIP magazine]]'': \"I think their song 'One' is one of the greatest songs ever written. Now I can see and understand why people were into U2 years ago.\"<ref name=James>James, Del. [http://www.w-axl-rose.com/Articles/Art_RIP_1992.html  I, AXL], ''[[RIP Magazine]]'' 1992</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{Quote box\n| quote=\"'One' [...] is certainly a breakup song. But it's also very much about the duty to stay together, about finding some kind of connection in times of war, fragmentation, plague, poverty and cultural difference. About being too cynical to believe in the hippie version of global oneness, but too much of a believer to reject it.\"\n| source = \u2014''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| width = 25%\n| align = right\n| style = padding:8px;\n}}\n\"One\" has frequently appeared on lists of the greatest songs. In 2010, ''Rolling Stone'' placed the song at number 36 on its list of \"[[The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\", making it the highest-ranked U2 song.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/u2-one-20110525|title=500 Greatest Songs of All Time: U2, 'One'|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|year=2010|issue=Special collectors edition}}</ref> In 2003, a special edition issue of ''Q'', titled \"1001 Best Songs Ever\", named \"One\" the greatest song of all-time.<ref>{{cite journal|title=1001 Best Songs Ever|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|author=Trynka, Paul (editor-in-chief)|year=2003|issue=Special edition}}</ref> [[VH1]] ranked the song second on its list of \"Greatest Songs of the 90s\",<ref name=\"vh190s\">{{cite episode|title=100 Greatest Songs of the 90s (Hour 5)|series=[[The Greatest (TV series)|The Greatest]]|network=[[VH1]]|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=127763|number=182|airdate=14 December 2007}}</ref> and voters in an April 2006 poll on VH1 named the song as having the UK's number-one lyric: \"One life, with each other, sisters, brothers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4915848.stm|title=U2 line tops favourite lyric poll|work=[[BBC News Online]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=17 April 2006|accessdate=8 September 2009}}</ref> In 2005, ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' ranked the song at number four on its list of \"The 500 Greatest Songs Since You Were Born\".<ref name=\"blender500\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.listal.com/list/500-greatest-songs-since-you |title=The 500 Greatest Songs Since You Were Born|journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|date=October 2005|issue=41|accessdate=24 April 2015}}</ref> The following year, readers of ''Q'' voted \"One\" the fifth-greatest song in history.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=The 100 Greatest Songs Ever!|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|date=October 2006|issue=243}}</ref> The song subsequently appeared as one of seven U2 songs in the 2006 music reference book ''[[1001 Songs]]: The Great Songs of All Time and the Artists, Stories, and Secrets''.<ref name=\"creswell\">Creswell (2006), pp. 415\u2013416</ref> It is included in [[the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll]].<ref>http://rockhall.com/exhibits/500-songs-that-shaped-rock-and/</ref>\n\nOn 31 December 2006, \"One\" was announced by [[BBC Radio 1]] to be the thirty-fifth highest-selling single of 2006 in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/chart/top40_2006.shtml|title=The Official UK Singles Chart of the year: 2006|work=[[BBC Radio 1]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=11 October 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215025341/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/chart/top40_2006.shtml|archivedate=15 December 2007 }}</ref> The collaboration was also nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals]] in December 2006.\n\nIn late 2006, a [[Bank of America]] employee sang \"One\" with lyrics modified to refer to the Bank of America and [[MBNA]] merger. The video subsequently became an [[internet meme|Internet phenomenon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ifilm.com/video/2795634 |title=One Bank |accessdate=3 January 2007 |format=|work= }}</ref> [[Universal Music Group]], the copyright owner of the song, posted a cease and desist letter directed at Bank of America in the comments section of [[Stereogum]], one of the blogs that posted the video.<ref name=\"New_York_Times\">{{cite news |last=Aspan |first=Mario |title=Lyrics Celebrating Bank Merger Impress Only Copyright Lawyer |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/20/business/media/20bank.html?ei=5090&en=7a77f2691e38a9d8&ex=1321678800&adxnnl=1&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss&adxnnlx=1167338226-NsOMIpdJNF94ZILt4sO+7Q |work=New York Times |date=20 November 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\n[[File:VertigoTour20051014 One.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Cellphones open as \"One\" is performed on the [[Vertigo Tour]], [[Madison Square Garden]], 14 October 2005.]]\n\"One\" made its live debut on 29 February 1992 in [[Lakeland, Florida]] on the opening night of the [[Zoo TV Tour]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.u2gigs.com/One-s21.html | title = U2 One | publisher = U2Gigs | accessdate = 2 May 2010}}</ref> and it was played at every subsequent show on U2's concert tours until the first show of the [[Innocence + Experience Tour]] in Vancouver, where it was not played for the first time in its history. However, the song returned for the following concert, when it was used as the show closer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/live-reviews/u2-honor-b-b-king-mock-the-edges-fall-at-second-show-20150516|title=U2 Honor B.B. King, Mock the Edge's Fall At Second Show|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=Andy|last=Greene|date=16 May 2015|accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref> Zoo TV performances were accompanied by footage from the second music video being displayed on the stage's video screens, with [[David Wojnarowicz]]'s \"Falling Buffalo\" photograph appearing at the end of the song.<ref name=\"nyt031192\">{{cite news| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/11/arts/review-rock-u2-restyled-with-props-and-a-nod-to-the-fringes.html |title = U2 Restyled, With Props and a Nod to the Fringes|first= Jon|last= Pareles|authorlink= Jon Pareles|newspaper = [[The New York Times]]|date=11 March 1992|page= C17}}</ref>\n\nThe song took on an even more emotional meaning at a [[Popmart Tour]] show at Mexico City in 1997, as featured on ''[[PopMart: Live from Mexico City]]'', where the tearful rendition was dedicated to [[Michael Hutchence]] of [[INXS]]. Until the second leg of the [[U2 360\u00b0 Tour]], \"One\" was played live in the key of A{{music |flat}} minor, while the recorded version is played a [[semitone]] higher.  Throughout its history, Bono has often sung the song with an extra verse generally known as \"Hear Us Coming\", whose lyrics are usually some variation of:\n<poem>You hear us coming Lord?\nYou hear us call?\nYou hear us knocking, knocking at Your door?\nYou hear us coming, Lord?\nYou hear us call?\nYou hear us scratching, will You make me crawl?</poem>\n\nIt was a nearly-regular feature on the Zoo TV Tour, PopMart, and [[Elevation Tour|Elevation]] Tours, but was sung less often on the Vertigo Tour. The verse made a re-emergence on the 2009 legs of the [[U2 360\u00b0 Tour]]; although it was not a nightly feature, Bono sang it very often, segueing into \"[[Amazing Grace]]\" and from there into \"[[Where the Streets Have No Name]]\" on most of the second leg. \"One\" has also been played at several benefit concerts, including the 1995 ''[[Pavarotti and Friends]]'' concert in Modena, the 1997 [[Tibetan Freedom Concert]] in New York, the 2003 [[46664 (concerts)|46664]] concert, at [[Live 8]] in 2005, and with Mary J. Blige on ''[[Shelter from the Storm: A Concert for the Gulf Coast]]''.\n\nLive performances of the song are also depicted in the concert films ''[[Zoo TV: Live from Sydney]]'', ''[[U2 Go Home: Live from Slane Castle]]'', ''[[Vertigo 2005: Live from Chicago]]'', ''[[U2 3D]]'', and ''[[U2 360\u00b0 at the Rose Bowl]]''.\n\n==Track listings==\nThe single was released on various formats including [[gramophone record|7-inch]], [[12-inch single|12-inch]], [[cassette single|cassette]], and [[Compact Disc single|CD]].  All releases featured a new song \"Lady with the Spinning Head (UV1)\" as a B-side track. This version was later included in the 20th anniversary release of ''Achtung Baby'', whereas an extended 'dance' remix was included on the double album version of ''[[The Best of 1990\u20132000]]''. Some releases also included \"Satellite of Love\" or both \"Satellite of Love\" and the \"Night and Day\" remix.\n\n{{tracklist\n|extra_column=Producer\n|title1=One\n|length1=4:36\n|lyrics1=Bono\n|music1=U2\n|extra1={{flatlist|\n* Daniel Lanois\n* Brian Eno\n}}\n|title2=Lady with the Spinning Head (UV1)\n|length2=3:54\n|lyrics2=Bono\n|music2=U2\n|extra2=Paul Barrett\n|title3=[[Satellite of Love]]\n|length3=4:00\n|lyrics3=[[Lou Reed]]\n|music3=Reed\n|extra3=The Edge and Barrett\n|title4=[[Night and Day (song)|Night and Day]]\n|length4=7:00\n|note4=Steel String remix\n|lyrics4=[[Cole Porter]]\n|music4=Porter\n|extra4=The Edge and Barrett\n}}\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''U2'''<ref name=\"album\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Achtung Baby|others=[[U2]]|year=1991|publisher=[[Island Records]]|type=CD booklet}}</ref>\n*[[Bono]]&nbsp;\u2013 vocals, guitar on \"Lady with the Spinning Head\"\n*[[The Edge]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar\n*[[Adam Clayton]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass guitar\n*[[Larry Mullen, Jr.|Larry Mullen Jr.]]&nbsp;\u2013 drums, percussion\n'''Additional performers'''<ref name=\"album\" />\n*[[Brian Eno]]&nbsp;\u2013 additional keyboards\n*[[Daniel Lanois]]&nbsp;\u2013 additional guitar\n{{col-break}}\n'''Technical'''<ref name=\"album\" />\n*Production&nbsp;\u2013 Daniel Lanois with Brian Eno\n*[[Audio engineering|Engineering]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Flood (producer)|Flood]]\n*Additional engineering&nbsp;\u2013 Robbie Adams\n*Engineering assistance&nbsp;\u2013 Shannon Strong\n*[[Audio mixing (recorded music)|Mixing]]&nbsp;\u2013 Flood\n*Mixing assistance&nbsp;\u2013 Shannon Strong\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sorta